WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:08.000
Hello everyone, I am Chetan. I am on the product team at Posit where I own our Snowflake integration.

00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:18.000
And today I will show you how we deliver on AI-Powered R & Python Data Science You Can Actually Trust.

00:00:18.000 --> 00:00:23.000
Three parts. Let's start with the problem and the context.

00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:28.000
So picture this. A data scientist gets access to a Snowflake database.

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:37.000
They open the table and hours later a VP is making decisions from the same data product that this data scientist built.

00:00:37.000 --> 00:00:42.000
Now what happened in between is the crux of this talk.

00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:47.000
Specifically, three things had to hold up for this decision to be trustworthy.

00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:50.000
Number one, an analytical collaborator.

00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:59.000
So a data science agent which knew when to lead, when to ask and when to use the methods that your team trusts.

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:01.000
We call this calibrated autonomy.

00:01:01.000 --> 00:01:13.000
Second, a dynamic data product. Not some pre-built widgets, but one that answered her follow-up questions live, composed new plots on the fly, all governed by her access.

00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:16.000
And third, trust end-to-end.

00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:23.000
Nothing is a black box. Everything is code backed. Everything reproduces.

00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:29.000
And all of that is powered by the positive native app running inside Snowflake.

00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:36.000
Two things worth knowing here. Firstly, Posit. We are the company behind some of the most widely used open source data science tools on the planet.

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:44.000
Creators of RStudio, Positron, Shiny. Millions of weekly users. Everything code backed with an open source foundation.

00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:52.000
And that is not incidental. That is why the trust story holds up when you add AI agents to the mix.

00:01:52.000 --> 00:02:00.000
On the right, you see Positive Native App. This is our enterprise data science platform running natively on Snowpark container services.

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:06.000
So fully managed from a data scientist exploring a table to a VP making a decision.

00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:16.000
Explore to consume all inside your Snowflake account, your perimeter, your RBAC inherited, and cortex LLMs that just work out of the box.

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:25.000
And one thing worth calling out explicitly is this is the only managed R runtime on Snowflake.

00:02:25.000 --> 00:02:35.000
Python and R both are first-class citizens, which makes it the only place on Snowflake where your multilingual data science teams have.

00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:44.000
OK, let's move to the demo. I'm going to start as a data scientist who's logged into the Positive Native App.

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:50.000
And let's go through that flow. So I start firstly with Workbench.

00:02:50.000 --> 00:03:00.000
This is our developer tool. And I'm going to launch a new session in Positron, which is our data science IDE, which has a unified agent as well.

00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:07.000
And my credentials and RBAC are inherited. So when I open a new project, you can see the cortex LLMs.

00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:14.000
They just are available out of the box. And so I ask a data science agent to explore a table.

00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:24.000
And it invokes a Snowflake skill based on the context and then connects easily to that table and gives me a snapshot of the data set.

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:30.000
It's about two and a quarter million loans. And a couple of things start catching my eye.

00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:39.000
Number one, there seem to be some data hygiene issues as well as there is a semantic model available.

00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:44.000
So I go with the first recommendation of the agent and ask to look at a semantic model.

00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:53.000
Now, this is something that my organization has created and defines things which are business specific like leakage ratio and net revenue.

00:03:53.000 --> 00:04:00.000
So when agents do the analysis, they know exactly what that means versus relying on their training data.

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:04.000
OK, now let's do some data cleaning as I enable the cleaning mode.

00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:13.000
And I just point the agent towards the table and say, hey, if there is data being needed, let's just do it.

00:04:13.000 --> 00:04:17.000
And that starts an audit. And this is the first calibrated autonomy moment.

00:04:17.000 --> 00:04:25.000
Now, instead of going off on its own, the agent is using judgment to surface choices as recommendations.

00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:32.000
It's flagging what needs attention. The agent suggests, I decide.

00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:42.000
And it just doesn't clean the data memory, it's asking me to create a clean view or table within Snowflake.

00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:52.000
And then it builds a script. So even the cleaning process is reproducible a month or six months from now.

00:04:52.000 --> 00:05:00.000
OK, now after this is done, I can actually see the clean Snowflake view that the agent has created from within the ID.

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:07.000
I can see the stats, I can see the shape of the data, I can see the raw data, all of that.

00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:10.000
Now that the data cleaning is done, I want to do some actual analysis.

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:16.000
So I ask the agent to find factors which are impacting the interest rate in this data set.

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:22.000
And it invokes a custom skill. Now, this skill has been built by my team.

00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:31.000
And the reason is we have a specific pipeline of steps that are certified and validated for any kind of driver analysis.

00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:38.000
These are real methods of how to do R-squared decomposition, specific visualizations that my team has standardized.

00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:43.000
And the skill does that along with giving me reproducibility information.

00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:52.000
And then at the end, summarizing the factors which are influencing the interest rate.

00:05:52.000 --> 00:06:01.000
Now, for the next step, I ask the agent to run the same analysis, but segmented by prime versus subprime borrowers.

00:06:01.000 --> 00:06:05.000
So firstly, the agent decides what prime versus subprime means based on context.

00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:12.000
And then it is running the same exact pipeline, the same six steps, but with new parameters.

00:06:12.000 --> 00:06:18.000
That's reproducibility. You can see side by side compare graphically.

00:06:18.000 --> 00:06:28.000
And at the end, the table with the pattern summarized and some strong suggestions.

00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:35.000
OK, now let's take it into a different direction. So I'm going to ask the agent to build a predictive model with this analysis.

00:06:35.000 --> 00:06:42.000
And the agent fires out the box skill, which we ship with Posit Assistant.

00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:50.000
And the first thing it's going to do is take the sample set and split it into test versus frame and provides me a baseline.

00:06:50.000 --> 00:06:59.000
And although it's a bit naive, it provides me a natural next step, which is to perform a linear regression with a median prediction and standard scalars.

00:06:59.000 --> 00:07:05.000
I take that recommendation and the CV results are coming back.

00:07:05.000 --> 00:07:11.000
And OK, R squared. But let's look at the next suggestion.

00:07:11.000 --> 00:07:18.000
It sees that the linear regression didn't capture the non-linearity, so it recommends a gradient boosting regressor.

00:07:18.000 --> 00:07:33.000
So this is a senior data scientist call. But what is the rhythm here? The agent suggests and I decide.

00:07:33.000 --> 00:07:40.000
OK, so we see the models plateauing here and the agents suggesting now a hyper parameter tuned.

00:07:40.000 --> 00:07:46.000
And I tell it to stop and validate instead of the holdout test set.

00:07:46.000 --> 00:07:50.000
And this is another calibrated autonomy moment. The agents suggesting the next step in judgment.

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:55.000
But I don't want to run a computationally expensive hyper parameter sweep without me in the loop.

00:07:55.000 --> 00:08:00.000
We got the residual plots back and this is looking good.

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:08.000
So at this stage, I say I want to keep this analysis for posterity, maybe for me for tomorrow or share it with my peers.

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:13.000
And all I need to do is write slash report.

00:08:13.000 --> 00:08:23.000
And that's going to invoke a scale and provide me an outline of all of the analysis that we have done and outline of the talk.

00:08:23.000 --> 00:08:27.000
And now I can always change this. But right now it makes sense.

00:08:27.000 --> 00:08:34.000
So I say, yes, let's go ahead with it. And this will start building that quarter document.

00:08:34.000 --> 00:08:39.000
You can also build a notebook if you so prefer.

00:08:39.000 --> 00:08:43.000
I think this is about seven hundred lines or eight hundred lines.

00:08:43.000 --> 00:08:51.000
And once this is done, because we are in Postron, we can just click on the preview button and see this this document.

00:08:51.000 --> 00:09:03.000
OK, so this is the table which we worked on. It has all of the code, the environment information and the summary, the analysis.

00:09:03.000 --> 00:09:09.000
This is not a chat log. This is an analytical artifact that can also be version controlled.

00:09:09.000 --> 00:09:16.000
Six months from now, someone on my team opens this, runs it, they get the same answer.

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:24.000
Again, reproducibility. For the next step now, I say let's turn this into an interactive data product.

00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:29.000
Let's turn this into a shiny app and connect it to snowflake data.

00:09:29.000 --> 00:09:38.000
And here I gave a very vague prompt. And this is the other side of calibrated autonomy.

00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:44.000
Because building a shiny app is the output is so verifiable.

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:56.000
We believe in that case, human in the loop can just be friction. And so the agent just zero shots this.

00:09:56.000 --> 00:10:04.000
So I can go and see that the agent created and press the play button to get a preview of this.

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:11.000
So the app seems to have good bones. It has the driver analysis as well as the predictive model.

00:10:11.000 --> 00:10:18.000
But let's say I want to take it up a notch and I want to add a natural language forward UI, which is driven by context.

00:10:18.000 --> 00:10:24.000
And so I can do all of that with positive assistant. For sake of time, I've already built that up.

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:37.000
And let me just load that into the new project and show you how that looks.

00:10:37.000 --> 00:10:43.000
OK, so you see, as it's loading up on the left side, you have a natural language UI where you can ask questions.

00:10:43.000 --> 00:10:51.000
And on the right, you have some prebuilt widgets which have the same lending cloud database, the two and a quarter million loads.

00:10:51.000 --> 00:10:57.000
And then I have a couple of tabs here on state analysis. And there's some load details there as well.

00:10:57.000 --> 00:11:04.000
OK, so this looks good. And now to ship it, all I need to do is literally click one button, deploy your project.

00:11:05.000 --> 00:11:21.000
And all of the open source dependencies, all of that is being packaged and being shipped to Connect, which is our publishing or hosting platform.

00:11:21.000 --> 00:11:31.000
And I go to the positive landing page, click on Connect, and I can see this data product that was just published here.

00:11:31.000 --> 00:11:43.000
And I can see this app now running in Connect. And to share it with anyone, I just need to go to the UI and copy the URL and then share it with them.

00:11:43.000 --> 00:11:50.000
And I can also add specific Snowflake roles to share with a full group.

00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:59.000
OK, great. So now let's move to the next chapter. Let's see how end users interact with this product.

00:11:59.000 --> 00:12:06.000
So now I'm the end user, the VP from our opening story. She has the app, opens it, logs in with her SSO.

00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:12.000
And she's looking at all of the widgets. Yeah, this is what I'd asked for. So it makes sense.

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:16.000
But I want to ask now some small business loads. I want to just see those.

00:12:16.000 --> 00:12:27.000
So I ask that question that has text to SQL powered by Cortex and the whole dashboard updates, the whole dashboard reacts, including all of the tabs that are there.

00:12:27.000 --> 00:12:34.000
This is great. This is at par with what I expected. And now I ask a question about leakage ratio.

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:40.000
Now, that's not defined anywhere in the dashboard here. And the agent comes back with the right answer.

00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:44.000
And more interestingly, leakage ratio was defined in a semantic model.

00:12:44.000 --> 00:12:51.000
And as you can see, the agent did a select start from semantic view. So this these interactions are semantically aware.

00:12:51.000 --> 00:12:57.000
Now, for the next step, I want to look at a baseline plot. Now, this is not anywhere on this dashboard.

00:12:57.000 --> 00:13:04.000
Neither is it a cookie cutter kind of a chart. So let's see how the agent handles it.

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:14.000
There you have it. Because we use grammar of graphics, we can compose these incredibly rich visualizations on the fly.

00:13:14.000 --> 00:13:18.000
And if you look at the query that was used to generate this, it's only six lines of SQL code.

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:25.000
So reproducible, easily understandable and frankly, graceful.

00:13:25.000 --> 00:13:31.000
OK, for my last question, I asked something about a little sensitive data type.

00:13:31.000 --> 00:13:38.000
So I asked about building a heat map with employment length, loan purpose and default rate with a specific color palette.

00:13:38.000 --> 00:13:42.000
And again, the agent is able to compose this dynamically.

00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:51.000
And I can see there are a few loan purposes where the default rate is higher and the employment length has some impact on it.

00:13:51.000 --> 00:13:59.000
OK, so at this stage, I have what I need. But now an analyst on my team, she logs in on the same app.

00:13:59.000 --> 00:14:04.000
But she's seeing only half a million loans instead of two and a quarter million loans.

00:14:04.000 --> 00:14:11.000
And I can ask the same question, which is around employment length and building that heat map.

00:14:11.000 --> 00:14:17.000
And let's see what the agent does.

00:14:17.000 --> 00:14:23.000
So the agent mentions that the employment length column is masked for her.

00:14:23.000 --> 00:14:31.000
And what we saw here was the same app, two different users getting two different answers.

00:14:31.000 --> 00:14:40.000
And that's because we are able to inherit and extend your data governance, your Snowflake role-based access.

00:14:40.000 --> 00:14:45.000
So we went through a lot there. We went through the end-to-end data science workflow,

00:14:45.000 --> 00:14:52.000
starting from connecting to a table all the way to interacting with a data product all within the Snowflake perimeter.

00:14:52.000 --> 00:15:01.000
And three key things to take away. Number one, we used an analytical collaborator for building a data product.

00:15:01.000 --> 00:15:05.000
We had a data science agent that used calibrated autonomy.

00:15:06.000 --> 00:15:12.000
Secondly, we had dynamic natural language visualizations.

00:15:12.000 --> 00:15:20.000
So end-user asked questions, charts were composed on the fly, governed by access, respecting semantic models,

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:27.000
not pre-built widgets, dynamic data products. And finally, trust, which we saw end-to-end.

00:15:27.000 --> 00:15:33.000
Everything was code backed, everything reproduced, even my team's validated methods.

00:15:33.000 --> 00:15:38.000
I was able to reproduce them by using an agent to orchestrate the workflow.

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:45.000
If any of this resonated, we encourage you to try out the POSIS Team Native app.

00:15:45.000 --> 00:15:52.000
You can scan this QR code or we'll leave a URL for you to click and get started.

00:15:52.000 --> 00:15:58.000
It's available on the marketplace and you get a free 30-day trial during onboarding. Thank you.

